{"id":"math/0605182","submitter":"Joseph Lewittes","authors":"Joseph Lewittes","title":"Midy's Theorem for Periodic Decimals","comments":"19 pagesthe","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT math.GM","license":null,"abstract":"  The decimal expansion of 1/7 is 0.142857142857..., the block 142857 repeating\nforever. We call 142857 the period and its length is 6 = 2x3. If the period is\nbroken into 2 pieces each of length 3 which are then added, the result is 142 +\n857 = 999; similarly 14 + 28 + 57 = 99. Other periodic decimals show the same\nphenomenon while others do not. The general question then arises: Let a/N be a\nfraction with denominator prime to 10, having decimal expansion with period\nlength dk, if the period is broken into d pieces of length k which are then\nadded, when will the sum be 99...9, a block of k 9's? In 1836 E. Midy published\nan article analyzing this question and gave sufficient conditions in certain\ncases. We put the problem in a more general setting, working in an arbitrary\nnumber base B, and obtain new results. However, some open questions still\nremain.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 7 May 2006 18:00:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
